        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(telegram): bound getChat Bot API response reads",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\r\n\r\n`fetchTelegramChatId()` (`getChat`) still parsed successful Bot API responses with unbounded `res.json()`. A misbehaving or hostile endpoint can stream an oversized body before chat-id lookup returns, risking gateway OOM during onboarding, routing, or chat-id normalization.\r\n\r\nThis is a follow-up to the other Telegram Bot API bound-read work (`getMe`, `getWebhookInfo`, `getChatMember`, `getUpdates`).\r\n\r\n## Why This Change Was Made\r\n\r\n- Replace the single success-path `res.json()` in `extensions/telegram/src/api-fetch.ts` with `readResponseWithLimit` (4 MiB cap), matching the Telegram probe/ingress bound-read contract.\r\n- Add a pass-through mock in `api-fetch.test.ts` so existing plain-object fetch stubs keep working.\r\n\r\n## User Impact\r\n\r\nNormal `getChat` responses are tiny (< 1 KiB). Operators only see a behavior change when a Bot API endpoint returns an abnormally large success body; in that case lookup now fails closed (`null`) instead of buffering unbounded JSON.\r\n\r\n## Evidence\r\n\r\n```\r\npnpm test extensions/telegram/src/api-fetch.test.ts\r\n\r\n Test Files  1 passed (1)\r\n      Tests  7 passed (7)\r\n```\r\n",
